Exit fullscreen mode

What changed?

•
Short‑lived access token (5 min) lives only in memory; stealing it gives a tiny window.

•
Refresh token is a random identifier (jti) stored in an httpOnly cookie—JavaScript can’t read it, mitigating XSS.

•
Refresh token rotation: on each use we delete the old jti and issue a new one, turning token‑theft into a race condition the attacker almost certainly loses.

•
Secrets are pulled from environment variables, not baked into source.

•
Logout simply revokes the refresh token in Redis, instantly killing the ability to get new access tokens.

If you wanted to add OAuth (Google, GitHub, etc.), you’d replace the /login handler with the provider’s redirect flow, exchange the auth code for tokens, then issue your own refresh/access pair exactly as shown. The core idea stays the same: trust the provider for identity, but manage your own session tokens.

Why This New Power Matters

Now you can build APIs that feel like they’re guarded by the Agents from The Matrix—fast, stateless, yet with a tight inner circle that’s hard to breach.

•
Frontend SPA devs can keep the access token in a React state hook or a Vuex store, knowing it’ll expire quickly and won’t survive a page refresh unless they hit /token.

•
Server‑side rendered apps can still use classic express-session for CSRF tokens while relying on JWTs for API calls.

•
Micro‑service architectures gain stateless validation (no need to hit a session store on every request) while still being able to revoke misbehaving clients instantly via the refresh‑token revocation list.

In short: you get the best of both worlds—security without sacrificing developer ergonomics.

Your Turn

Try swapping the naïve JWT implementation in your own project for the layered version above. Play with the refresh‑token rotation: deliberately steal a cookie (you can’t, but imagine) and see how fast the window closes.

Challenge: Add a third‑party OAuth provider (Google works nicely) to the /login route, then issue your own refresh/access tokens after the provider returns the user info. Share your snippet in the comments—I’d love to see how you wired it up!

Happy hacking, and may your tokens stay short‑lived and your cookies stay httpOnly! 🚀
